# Use & sync the frontend-ui skill

The skill at [`.claude/skills/frontend-ui/SKILL.md`](.claude/skills/frontend-ui/SKILL.md) is the single source of truth for:

- Reusable components catalog (`apps/frontend/src/components/**`)
- Design tokens, semantic colors, `textStyle`/`size` scales
- Recipe variants (`apps/frontend/src/app/theme/*.ts`)
- Style patterns (mobile-first, modal/bottom-sheet split, card/button/badge usage, i18n)

## Before writing frontend code

**Read the skill first.** Then:

1. Check the catalog in SKILL.md §3 before creating a new component — reuse existing ones.
2. Use semantic tokens from §2 for every color / typography decision. No hex, no raw `fontSize`/`lineHeight`, no font weights other than `normal`/`semibold`/`bold`.
3. Match the patterns in §4 (mobile-first, `BaseModal`, `Card.Root` variants, `StatCard`/`EmptyStateCard`, `FormItem`, `TransactionModal`).

## Update the skill in the same commit when your change touches any of

- **New / renamed / deleted shared component** in `apps/frontend/src/components/` → update §3 table
- **New / removed recipe variant** in `apps/frontend/src/app/theme/*.ts` → update §2 cheat sheet
- **New / removed / renamed semantic token** in `apps/frontend/src/app/theme/theme.ts` (tokens or semanticTokens) → update §2 semantic colors table
- **New house pattern** (new modal shell, toast, skeleton convention, etc.) → add to §4
- **Deprecation** — mark the old row "deprecated — use X instead" in §3, don't delete outright
- **New `textStyle` scale entry** or font-weight policy change → update §2 typography

No skill update needed for:

- Purely internal refactor of a component (no exported shape change, no new token usage)
- Bug fixes without behaviour change
- Translation-only edits
- Business logic / data fetching changes that don't touch style or exported UI primitives

## Constraints when editing the skill

- Keep it **under 500 lines**
- Prefer **updating existing tables** over adding sections
- Don't paste implementation code — link to the file path
- Don't document feature-specific internals here (feature skills exist for that, e.g. `challenges`)
